The '''1880 Greenback Party National Convention''' convened at the Interstate Exposition Building in [[Chicago]] from June 9 to 11, 1880, to select presidential and vice-presidential nominees and write a [[party platform]] for the [[Greenback Party]] in the [[United States presidential election, 1880|United States presidential election of 1880]]. Delegates chose [[James B. Weaver]] of [[Iowa]] for President and [[Barzillai J. Chambers]] of [[Texas]] for Vice President.

The Greenback Party was a newcomer to the political scene in 1880, having arisen, mostly in the nation's West and South, as a response to the economic depression that followed the [[Panic of 1873]]. During the [[American Civil War]], Congress had authorized "[[United States Note|greenbacks]]," a form of money redeemable in government bonds, rather than in gold, as was traditional. After the war, many Democrats and Republicans in the East sought to return to the gold standard, and the government began to withdraw greenbacks from circulation. The reduction of the [[money supply]], combined with the economic depression, made life harder for debtors, farmers, and industrial laborers; the Greenback Party hoped to draw support from these groups.

Six men were candidates for the presidential nomination. Weaver, an Iowa congressman and Civil War general, was the clear favorite, but two other congressmen, [[Benjamin Butler (politician)|Benjamin F. Butler]] of Massachusetts and [[Hendrick B. Wright]] of Pennsylvania, also commanded considerable followings. Weaver triumphed quickly, winning a majority of the 850 delegates' votes on the first ballot. Chambers, a Texas businessman and [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] veteran, was likewise nominated on the initial vote. More tumultuous was the fight over the platform, as delegates from disparate factions of the left-wing movement clashed over [[Women's suffrage in the United States|women's suffrage]], [[History of Chinese Americans|Chinese immigration]], and the extent to which the government should regulate working conditions. Votes for women was the most contentious of these, with the party ultimately endorsing the suffragists' cause, despite a vocal minority's opposition.

Weaver and Chambers left the convention with high hopes for the [[Third party (United States)|third party]]'s cause, but in the end they were disappointed. The election was a close contest between the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], [[James A. Garfield]], and the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]], [[Winfield Scott Hancock]], with Garfield being the narrow victor. The Greenback ticket placed a distant third, netting just over three percent of the popular vote.

==Background==
===Origins===
[[File:US-$5-LT-1862-Fr-61a.jpg|thumb|An 1862 greenback five dollar bill]]
The [[Greenback Party]] was a newcomer to politics in 1880, having first nominated candidates for national office four years earlier.{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=29}} The party had arisen, mostly in the West and South, as a response to the economic depression that followed the [[Panic of 1873]].{{sfn|Lause|2001|pp=22<U+2013>23}} During the [[American Civil War|Civil War]], Congress had authorized "[[United States Note|greenbacks]]," a new form of [[fiat money]] that was redeemable not [[Gold standard|in gold]] but in government bonds.{{sfn|Unger|1964|pp=14<U+2013>15}} The greenbacks had helped to finance the war when the government's gold supply did not keep pace with the expanding costs of maintaining the armies. When the crisis had passed, many in both the Democratic and Republican parties, especially in the East, wanted to return the nation's currency to a gold standard as soon as possible (candidates who favored the gold-backed currency were called "hard money" supporters, while the policy of encouraging inflation was known as "soft money").{{sfn|Unger|1964|pp=16<U+2013>17}} The [[Specie Payment Resumption Act]], passed in 1875, ordered that greenbacks be gradually withdrawn and replaced with gold-backed currency beginning in 1879.{{sfn|Wiebe|1967|p=6}} At the same time, [[Long Depression|economic depression]] had made it more expensive for debtors to pay debts they had contracted when currency was less valuable.{{sfn|Unger|1964|pp=228<U+2013>233}} Neither the Democrats nor the Republicans offered a home to those who favored retaining the greenbacks, so many looked to create a third party that would address their concerns.{{sfn|Lause|2001|pp=26<U+2013>27}} Greenbackers drew support from the growing labor movement in the nation's Eastern cities as well as Western and Southern farmers who had been harmed by deflation.{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=28}} Beyond their support for a larger money supply, they also favored an [[Eight-hour day|eight-hour work day]], safety regulations in factories, and an end to [[Child labour|child labor]].{{sfn|Clancy|1958|pp=163<U+2013>164}} As one author put it, they "anticipated by almost fifty years the progressive legislation of the first quarter of the twentieth century".{{sfn|Clancy|1958|pp=163<U+2013>164}}

In 1876, various independent [[1876 Greenback National Convention|delegates gathered]] in [[Indianapolis]] to nominate a presidential ticket to campaign on those issues.{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=29}} For president, they chose [[Peter Cooper]], an eighty-five-year-old industrialist and philanthropist from New York, with [[Samuel Fenton Cary]], a former Congressman from Ohio, as his running mate.{{sfn|Lause|2001|pp=32<U+2013>33}} The Greenback ticket fared poorly in [[United States presidential election, 1876|the election]] that November, attracting just 81,740 votes<U+2014>less than 1% of the total.{{sfn|Lause|2001|pp=32<U+2013>33}} As bad economic times continued, however, the party gained momentum. Labor unrest the following year, culminating in the [[Great Railroad Strike of 1877]], added to many laborers' alienation from the two major parties.{{sfn|Lause|2001|pp=34<U+2013>35}} Local movements, like California's [[Workingmen's Party of California|Workingmen's Party]], began to agitate for laws to improve the condition of laborers (and for an end to [[History of Chinese Americans|Chinese immigration]]).{{sfn|Lause|2001|pp=36<U+2013>37}} By 1878, the third-party movement had become strong enough to elect 22 independents to the federal [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]], most tied in some way to the Greenback movement.{{sfn|Lause|2001|pp=36<U+2013>37}} As the 1880 presidential election approached, members of the Greenback Party (or Greenback-Labor Party, as it was sometimes known) had reason to believe that they could improve on the results of 1876.{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=38}}

===Party split===
Attempts to fuse the disparate state and local parties into a national force led to friction between party leaders.{{sfn|Doolen|1972|pp=442<U+2013>444}} By 1879, there was a clear split, as a group led by [[Marcus M. Pomeroy|Marcus M. "Brick" Pomeroy]] formed their own "Union Greenback Labor Party."{{sfn|Barr|1967|p=280}} Pomeroy's group of mostly Southern and Western Greenbackers was opposed to [[electoral fusion]] with either of the two major parties and took more radical positions on monetary policy, including payment of all federal bonds in greenbacks, rather than the gold dollars originally promised investors.{{sfn|Doolen|1972|pp=442<U+2013>444}} They also differed from the Eastern-centered rump party (often called the "National Greenback Party") in calling for the popular election of [[postmaster]]s and the [[Capital punishment|death penalty]] as punishment for corruption in public office.{{sfn|Doolen|1972|p=445}} After a January 1880 conference in [[Washington, D.C.]] failed to unite the factions, each party called for its own national convention to nominate candidates for president.{{sfn|Doolen|1972|p=445}}

The Union Greenbackers held their convention first, meeting in [[St. Louis]] in March 1880.{{sfn|Barr|1967|p=280}} Although much of the young party's leadership remained with the Eastern faction, the March gathering included [[Solon Chase]] and [[Kersey Graves]], among other third party notables.{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=49}} They nominated [[Stephen D. Dillaye]], a New Jersey lawyer and journalist, for President and [[Barzillai J. Chambers]], a Texas merchant and surveyor, for Vice President.{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=50}} Because Dillaye had previously declared he was not interested in the nomination, many delegates protested, seeing Dillaye as a placeholder for eventual re-unification with the National Greenbackers.{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=50}} Dillaye, himself, supported reunification, and Pomeroy also urged the delegates to send representatives to the Easterners' convention, which was set for June 1880 in Chicago.{{sfn|Doolen|1972|p=447}} The majority agreed with the sentiment, and Union Greenbackers gathered in Chicago along with National Greenbackers as their convention began a few months later.{{sfn|Doolen|1972|p=447}}

==Candidates==
===Weaver===
[[File:JamesWeaver.png|thumb|Representative [[James B. Weaver]] of Iowa]]
[[James B. Weaver|James Baird Weaver]] grew up on the [[Iowa]] frontier and was involved with the Republican Party from its early days in the late 1850s.{{sfn|Mitchell|2008|pp=7<U+2013>31}} At the outbreak of Civil War, he joined the Union Army.{{sfn|Mitchell|2008|p=35}} Weaver saw action at the battles of [[Battle of Fort Donelson|Fort Donelson]], [[Battle of Shiloh|Shiloh]], and [[Battle of Resaca|Resaca]], and rose to the rank of brevet brigadier general.{{sfn|Mitchell|2008|pp=39<U+2013>50}} After the war, he continued to be active in Iowa Republican politics. Weaver sought nomination to the House of Representatives and the Governorship, but each time was defeated by candidates from the party's more conservative faction, led by [[William B. Allison]].{{sfn|Mitchell|2008|pp=55<U+2013>59}} He campaigned for the Republican presidential candidate, [[Rutherford B. Hayes]], in 1876, but also attended the 1876 Greenback National Convention as an observer.{{sfn|Mitchell|2008|pp=68<U+2013>70}} 

By 1877, differences with party leadership on the money question led him to consider other options.{{sfn|Mitchell|2008|pp=68<U+2013>70}} After initially supporting the Republican candidate for governor that year, Weaver joined the Greenback Party in August.{{sfn|Colbert|1978|p=26}} In 1878, Weaver accepted the Greenback nomination for [[Iowa's 6th congressional district]].{{sfn|Mitchell|2008|p=74}} Although Weaver's political career up to then had been as a staunch Republican, Democrats in the 6th district considered that endorsing him was likely the only way to defeat [[Ezekiel S. Sampson]], the incumbent Republican.{{sfn|Colbert|1978|p=27}} Despite objections from some hard-money Democrats, the Greenback-Democrat ticket prevailed, and Weaver was elected with 16,366 votes to Sampson's 14,307.{{sfn|Colbert|1978|p=39}} 

Weaver entered the [[46th United States Congress|46th Congress]] in March 1879.{{sfn|Mitchell|2008|p=83}} Although the House was closely divided, neither major party included the Greenbackers in their caucus, leaving them few committee assignments and little input on legislation.{{sfn|Mitchell|2008|p=84}} Weaver gave his first speech in April 1879, criticizing the use of the army to police Southern polling stations, while also decrying [[Disenfranchisement after the Reconstruction Era|the violence against black Southerners]] that made such protection necessary; he then described the Greenback platform, which he said would put an end to the sectional and economic strife.{{sfn|Mitchell|2008|pp=86<U+2013>87}} The next month, he spoke in favor of a bill calling for an increase in the money supply by allowing the [[Free silver|unlimited coinage of silver]], but the bill was easily defeated.{{sfn|Mitchell|2008|pp=86<U+2013>87}} Weaver's oratorical skill drew praise, and while he was unable to advance Greenback policy ideas, he was soon considered the front-runner for the presidential nomination in 1880.{{sfn|Mitchell|2008|pp=88<U+2013>89}}

===Butler===
[[File:Bfbutler.jpg|thumb|left|Former Representative [[Benjamin Butler (politician)|Benjamin F. Butler]] of Massachusetts]]
[[Benjamin Butler (politician)|Benjamin Franklin Butler]] was born in [[Deerfield, New Hampshire]], and later moved to Massachusetts to pursue a legal career.{{sfn|Fish|1929|p=357}} He built a successful practice in the 1840s and 1850s and became involved in local politics as a Democrat.{{sfn|Fish|1929|p=357}} A compelling public speaker, Butler was first elected to the [[Massachusetts House of Representatives]] in 1853.{{sfn|Fish|1929|p=357}} He successfully ran for a [[Massachusetts Senate]] seat in 1859.{{sfn|Fish|1929|p=357}} Despite his Protestant upbringing, he gained a faithful following among Massachusetts Catholics and also built support among laborers.{{sfn|Fish|1929|p=357}} In the 1860 presidential campaign, Butler sought compromise with the [[slave power]] and believed Senator [[Jefferson Davis]] of Mississippi should be the Democratic Party's nominee for president.{{sfn|Thompson|1982|p=165}}

Butler had been elected a brigadier general of the Massachusetts militia, and when the Civil War began in 1861, he quickly organized his men and marched south.{{sfn|Fish|1929|p=357}} Butler's men occupied [[Baltimore]] to ensure that Maryland did not follow its fellow Southern states into secession.{{sfn|Fish|1929|p=358}} In May of that year, he was promoted to major general and sent to command at [[Fort Monroe]] in Virginia, where he pioneered the tactic of seizing and freeing slaves as "[[Contraband (American Civil War)|contraband]] of war".{{sfn|Fish|1929|p=358}} When Union forces captured [[New Orleans]], Butler was sent to command there.{{sfn|Fish|1929|p=358}} Butler's rule was harsh, and he became especially reviled among Southern whites, to whom he was known as "Beast" Butler.{{sfn|Thompson|1982|p=165}} He was transferred to the Virginia theater in 1863, where he worked under General [[Ulysses S. Grant]]'s direction in the campaigns that led to the Confederacy's defeat.{{sfn|Fish|1929|p=358}} 

After the war, Butler was elected to Congress as a Republican, and soon came to identify with that party's [[Radical Republican|more radical element]].{{sfn|Fish|1929|p=358}} In 1868, he was among the leaders in President [[Andrew Johnson]]'s [[Impeachment of Andrew Johnson|impeachment]].{{sfn|Fish|1929|p=358}} Butler's wartime exploits earned him support among blacks and [[Abolitionism|abolitionist]]s, which, combined with his existing base among laborers, ensured his reelection for several terms.{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=53}} His radicalism made him enemies among conservative Republicans, however, and when he lost his seat in the [[United States House of Representatives elections, 1874|Democratic wave of 1874]], he began to shift his allegiance to the nascent Greenback Party.{{sfn|Fish|1929|p=359}} In 1876, he returned to the House as a Republican, but in 1878 he ran unsuccessfully for [[Governor of Massachusetts]] as an independent Greenbacker with Democratic support.{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=53}} Butler had supporters across the political spectrum<U+2014>he was often said to be "a member of all parties and false to each"<U+2014>and was considered a presidential possibility when the Greenbackers convened in Chicago in 1880.{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=53}}
{{-}}

===Wright===
[[File:HBWright.jpg|thumb|Representative [[Hendrick Bradley Wright|Hendrick B. Wright]] of Pennsylvania]]
[[Hendrick Bradley Wright]] was born and raised in northeastern Pennsylvania.{{sfn|Boyd|1936|p=553}} After studying law at [[Dickinson College]], Wright returned to [[Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania|Wilkes-Barre]] and quickly became known as a gifted attorney and orator.{{sfn|Clausen|1965|pp=201<U+2013>202}} His powers of speech earned him notice in Pennsylvania Democratic Party circles, as well as the nickname "Old-Man-Not-Afraid-To-Be-Called-A-Demagogue".{{sfn|Clausen|1965|pp=201<U+2013>202}} He became a district attorney for [[Luzerne County, Pennsylvania|Luzerne County]] in 1834 and was elected to the [[Pennsylvania House of Representatives]] in 1841.{{sfn|Boyd|1936|p=553}} Wright was reelected in 1842 and 1843, serving as Speaker in his final term.{{sfn|Boyd|1936|p=553}} He served as president of the [[1844 Democratic National Convention]], working with the anti-[[Martin Van Buren|Van Buren]] faction to prevent that former President's nomination.{{sfn|Clausen|1965|pp=203<U+2013>205}} After the convention, he sought a seat in the United States Senate, but was unsuccessful.{{sfn|Boyd|1936|p=553}}

Wright was defeated for election to the U.S. House of Representatives in 1850, but was successful in 1852.{{sfn|Boyd|1936|p=553}} Defeated for reelection in 1854, he ran in 1860 as a Democrat with Republican support, and was elected to represent [[Pennsylvania's 12th congressional district]].{{sfn|Clausen|1965|pp=203<U+2013>205}} He spoke against the [[Peace Democrat]]s early in the Civil War, but by 1864, believing the Union war aims had changed for the worse, he supported Democrat [[George B. McClellan]] for the presidency.{{sfn|Boyd|1936|p=553}} Wright did not run for reelection, returning to private life in 1863. He continued his legal career and published writings on the relationship between labor and capital.{{sfn|Boyd|1936|p=553}} His book, ''A Practical Treatise on Labor'', was published in 1871.{{sfn|Boyd|1936|p=553}}

In 1876, Wright was elected to his old seat in Congress as a Democrat, but with support from the small Greenback movement.{{sfn|Boyd|1936|p=554}} In 1878, the situation was reversed: Wright ran as a Greenbacker, but was reelected with support by Democrats.{{sfn|Boyd|1936|p=554}} He attracted attention in Congress with his proposal to amend the [[Homestead Acts|Homestead Act of 1862]] to establish government loans to would-be settlers of the West, making it easier for landless Easterners to claim homesteads there.{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=54}} Congress was, on the whole, not receptive to Wright's proposal.{{sfn|Deverell|1988|p=274}} Wright proposed it again in 1879 and emphasized the conservatism of his proposal, that it was a loan secured by the homestead, not a gift from the state; even so, the bill went down to overwhelming defeat.{{sfn|Deverell|1988|p=275}} Despite his failure, Wright, like Weaver, had raised his profile as a potential presidential nominee by attempting to advance Greenback ideas in Congress.{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=54}}

===Other contenders===
Several [[favorite son]] candidates had delegates interested in their nomination, although they were seen as having less of a chance of gaining the nomination.{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=54}} [[Alexander Campbell (Illinois politician)|Alexander Campbell]] had represented Illinois in the House of Representatives several years earlier. He was seen as a pragmatist who represented the Greenback Party's more conservative members. [[Henly James]] was the head of the [[The National Grange of the Order of Patrons of Husbandry|Grange]] in Indiana and had served in the state legislature there, but attracted little support outside his own delegation.{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=54}} In the Wisconsin delegation, many favored [[Edward P. Allis]], an industrialist who owned the Reliance Iron Works.{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=54}} Allis was a longtime supporter of soft money, but had no experience in elected office.{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=54}} Finally, [[Solon Chase]] of Maine had some support from the New England delegations.{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=54}} Chase was a publisher of a Greenback newspaper, ''Chase's Inquirer'', and had narrowly lost a House election in 1878.{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=55}} Chase was among the most radical of the Greenbackers, attracting support from the party's left-wing members.{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=55}}

