==Convention==
[[File:Interstate Exposition Building 1890.jpg|thumb|left|The Interstate Exposition Building in Chicago]]
===Preliminaries===
The National Greenback Party delegates assembled in the Interstate Exposition Building in Chicago on Wednesday, June 9, 1880.{{sfn|Kennedy et al.|1880|p=74}} The [[1880 Republican National Convention|Republican convention]] took place in the same building and had only just ended after a record 36 rounds of balloting.{{sfn|Clancy|1958|pp=115<U+2013>116}} When the Greenbackers arrived, the Republicans' banners still hung from the walls, so the delegates were greeted by images of [[Abraham Lincoln]] and [[Thaddeus Stevens]] as they entered.{{sfn|Mitchell|2008|p=99}} The building, popularly known as the "Glass Palace", had been built in 1873 for an Interstate Industrial Exposition.{{efn|After the Exposition, it hosted festivals and concerts for several years until it was demolished in 1892. The [[Art Institute of Chicago]] now stands on the site.{{sfn|Currey|1918|pp=152<U+2013>153}}}}{{sfn|Currey|1918|p=151}}

Franklin P. Dewees of the party's executive committee called the convention to order at 12:30 p.m. on June 9.{{sfn|Kennedy et al.|1880|p=74}} Reverend Pearl P. Ingalls of Iowa said a brief prayer, and the convention was opened.{{sfn|Kennedy et al.|1880|p=74}} [[Gilbert De La Matyr]], a Methodist minister and Greenback congressman from Indiana, was unanimously chosen as temporary chairman.{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=63}} After De La Matyr gave a brief, fiery speech, they proceeded to call the roll, which included delegates from every state except Oregon.{{sfn|Kennedy et al.|1880|p=75}} As the roll call finished, [[Matilda Joslyn Gage]], a [[suffragist]], mounted the stage, provoking cheers from some delegates and howls of outrage from others.{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=64}} She called for the new party to recognize women's right to vote, but the issue was avoided temporarily when the delegates voted to send her petition to a committee for further study.{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=65}}

===Reunification===
[[File:RichardTrevellick.jpg|thumb|upright|Richard Trevellick was the convention's permanent chairman.]]
The Union Greenback convention had reconvened at nearby Farwell Hall and sent an emissary to the National Greenbackers.{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=65}} The delegates voted to join the other faction in a special conference committee to work for reunification, then adjourned until 7:30 that evening.{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=65}} While they waited for the committees to finish their work, the delegates listened to speeches by several prominent Greenbackers, including [[Denis Kearney]], a California labor leader, and [[William Wallace (Canadian politician)|William Wallace]], a Canadian parliamentarian and advocate for currency reform.{{sfn|Kennedy et al.|1880|p=75}} Meanwhile, the Credentials Committee voted narrowly to admit the Union Greenbackers, as well as a delegation from the [[Socialist Labor Party of America|Socialist Labor Party]].{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=67}} The Committee on Permanent Organization voted to recommend [[Richard F. Trevellick]], a Michigan [[trade union]] organizer, as the permanent chairman of the convention.{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=67}} None of the reports were finished by the appointed time, so the convention adjourned again until 10:45 Thursday morning.{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=69}}

When they reconvened, the Credentials Committee announced that there were 608 regularly selected delegates, and recommended the admission of 185 Union Greenbackers and 44 Socialist Laborites, along with a handful of others.{{efn|The others included six from Chicago's Eight Hour League, three from the Chicago Workingwomen's Union, three from the Workingmen's Party of Kansas, and one from Chicago's Social Political Workingmen's Society.{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=70}}}}{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=70}} After a spirited and chaotic discussion, the convention voted to admit the other delegates in a voice vote: the party was reunified.{{sfn|Lause|2001|pp=71<U+2013>74}} Messages were sent to the Union Greenbackers and Socialist Laborites informing them of the results. In the meantime, the women's suffrage supporters again tried to convince the delegates to endorse their cause.{{sfn|Lause|2001|pp=74<U+2013>75}} [[Sarah Andrews Spencer]] mounted the stage to give an impassioned argument for women's right to vote, while Kearney climbed a nearby platform to shout his disapproval.{{sfn|Lause|2001|pp=74<U+2013>75}} Their informal debate was interrupted by a brass band announcing the arrival of the Union Greenbackers and Socialist Laborites.{{sfn|Lause|2001|pp=74<U+2013>75}} The convention erupted in prolonged cheering and a banner with the word "Reunion" was hoisted.{{sfn|Lause|2001|pp=74<U+2013>75}} The convention broke for a brief recess as the delegates renewed their acquaintance with the erstwhile schismatics.{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=76}}

===Platform===
[[File:Greenback factors.jpg|thumb|An 1880 cartoon in ''[[Frank Leslie's Illustrated Newspaper]]'' ridicules the Greenback party as a collection of disparate radicals.]]
The delegates voted to address the platform before deciding on nominees, and debate began when they reconvened at 8:45 p.m.{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=76}} Many fights and compromises had been hashed out in the Resolutions Committee already, but the delegates insisted on debating several provisions.{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=76}} On many planks, there was widespread agreement among the delegates. On the monetary issue, the platform declared that all money, whether metal or paper, should be issued by the government, not by banks (as was common for [[National Bank Note|paper money at the time]]).{{sfn|Mitchell|2008|pp=100<U+2013>101}} They also called for the unlimited coinage of silver and the repayment of the national debt in bonds, rather than gold dollars.{{sfn|Kennedy et al.|1880|p=81}} Other planks of the platform called for a graduated income tax, laws to mandate safe working conditions in factories, the regulation of interstate commerce, and an end to child and convict labor; all of these were familiar parts of Greenback platforms from earlier elections, and provoked no serious dissent.{{sfn|Mitchell|2008|pp=100<U+2013>101}}

Social issues provoked greater disagreement. Kearney's Western faction gained a victory when the platform was made to include a call for an end to Chinese immigration.{{sfn|Mitchell|2008|pp=100<U+2013>101}} They also turned, at last, to the issue of suffrage. They eventually agreed on a vague statement in the platform, that the party would "denounce as dangerous, the efforts everywhere manifest to restrict the right of suffrage".{{sfn|Kennedy et al.|1880|p=82}} Many of the delegates found this unsatisfying, and called for a separate resolution on the subject.{{sfn|Lause|2001|pp=77<U+2013>79}} After more debate, a resolution calling for the enfranchisement of "every citizen" passed by a vote of 528 to 124.{{sfn|Lause|2001|pp=77<U+2013>79}} The Socialist Labor faction proposed another resolution declaring "that land, air, and water are the grand gifts of nature to all mankind", and that no person had a right to monopolize them; the convention applauded, but the proposal was shunted off to a committee.{{sfn|Lause|2001|pp=77<U+2013>79}}

===Nominations and balloting===
It was nearly midnight Thursday night when the platform fights were finished, but the delegates voted to proceed immediately to nominations for President.{{sfn|Lause|2001|pp=79<U+2013>81}} At 1:00 Friday morning, the roll call began.{{sfn|Lause|2001|pp=79<U+2013>81}} S.F. Norton proposed his fellow Illinoisan, Alexander Campbell, proclaiming his great financial knowledge and association with Lincoln.{{sfn|Lause|2001|pp=79<U+2013>81}}{{sfn|Kennedy et al.|1880|pp=84<U+2013>85}} James Buchanan, the editor of the ''[[Indianapolis Sun]]'', proposed Benjamin Butler. Iowa Congressman [[Edward H. Gillette]] nominated Weaver, and Frank M. Fogg of Maine proposed "the farmer's friend", Solon Chase.{{sfn|Lause|2001|pp=79<U+2013>81}}{{sfn|Kennedy et al.|1880|pp=84<U+2013>85}} Perry Talbot of Missouri nominated the Union Greenbackers' nominee, Stephen D. Dillaye, who immediately asked that his name be withdrawn.{{sfn|Lause|2001|pp=79<U+2013>81}} Pennsylvania's delegation nominated Hendrick Wright, and Wisconsin's closed with the nomination of Edward P. Allis.{{sfn|Lause|2001|pp=79<U+2013>81}}

Now 3:25 a.m., the delegates took an informal ballot.{{sfn|Kennedy et al.|1880|pp=84<U+2013>85}} Weaver led the pack with about 30% of the votes, with Wright, Dillaye, and Butler trailing at about 15% each and the remaining votes scattered among the remaining candidates.{{efn|Contemporary accounts differ on the exact tally of the informal ballot, with various sources crediting Weaver with anywhere between 220 and 235 votes.{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=81}}{{sfn|Indiana Democrat 1880}}{{sfn|La Plata Home Press 1880}}}}{{sfn|Indiana Democrat 1880}} Supporters of Wright and Butler talked of combining their forces, but the momentum favored Weaver.{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=81}} In the first formal ballot, at 4:10 a.m., Weaver gained votes, and delegates began shifting their ballots to him.{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=81}} Without any official motion, the nomination was made unanimous, and the brass band again began to play.{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=81}} Weaver, who was staying at the nearby [[The Palmer House Hilton|Palmer House]] hotel, was summoned to the convention.{{sfn|Kennedy et al.|1880|p=86}} As they waited, the delegates turned to the Vice Presidential nomination. Some of Butler's supporters proposed nominating [[Absolom M. West]] of Mississippi, a more conservative Greenbacker, to balance the ticket against Weaver, whom they regarded as radical.{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=81}} West, who was present at the convention, had already disappointed the radicals by opposing women's suffrage and the eight-hour day.{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=81}} They instead proposed [[Barzillai J. Chambers]] of Texas, who had been the Union Greenbackers' nominee for 
Vice President.{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=81}} The majority agreed, as Chambers took 403 votes to West's 311.{{sfn|Kennedy et al.|1880|p=87}} 

Weaver had still not arrived, and the Socialist Labor delegates took the opportunity to call for a re-vote on their land plank and the women's suffrage issue.{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=81}} The delegates overruled the chairman's holding that the question was out of order and overwhelmingly voted that the "land, air, and water" plank and a plank explicitly supporting women's suffrage should be considered "part of the platform".{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=82}} Finally, at 6:00 a.m., Weaver arrived.{{sfn|Mitchell|2008|pp=100<U+2013>101}} To thunderous applause, the nominee thanked the convention for its decision and accepted the nomination.{{sfn|Mitchell|2008|pp=100<U+2013>101}} At 6:45 a.m., the exhausted delegates adjourned.{{sfn|Lause|2001|p=82}}

==Aftermath==
Three weeks later, Weaver published his formal letter of acceptance, calling for all party members to "go forth in the great struggle for human rights".{{sfn|Kennedy et al.|1880|p=94}} In a departure from the political traditions of the day, Weaver himself campaigned, making speeches across the South in July and August.{{sfn|Mitchell|2008|pp=102<U+2013>103}} As the Greenbackers had the only ticket that included a Southerner, Weaver and Chambers hoped to make inroads in the South.{{sfn|Lause|2001|pp=85<U+2013>104}} Chambers's own participation was limited, as before reaching home from the convention, he fell as he exited his train and broke two ribs.{{sfn|Barr|1967|p=282}} He was confined to bed for several weeks and considered withdrawing from the race, but decided against it; his efforts were limited by his injuries, and his only contribution to the campaign was to publish his newspaper.{{sfn|Barr|1967|p=282}}

As the campaign progressed, Weaver's message of racial inclusion drew violent protests in the South, as the Greenbackers faced the same obstacles the Republicans did in the face of increasing [[Disenfranchisement after the Reconstruction Era|black disenfranchisement]].{{sfn|Lause|2001|pp=105<U+2013>124}} In the autumn, Weaver campaigned in the North, but the Greenbackers' lack of support was compounded by Weaver's refusal to run a fusion ticket in states where Democratic and Greenbacker strength might have combined to outvote the Republicans.{{sfn|Lause|2001|pp=124<U+2013>146}}

The Greenback ticket received 305,997 votes and no electoral votes, compared to 4,446,158 for the winner, Republican James A. Garfield, and 4,444,260 for Democrat Winfield Scott Hancock.{{sfn|Ackerman|2003|p=221}} The party was strongest in the West and South, but in no state did Weaver receive more than 12% of the vote, and his nationwide total was just 3%.{{sfn|Mitchell|2008|p=111}} That figure represented an improvement over the Greenback vote of 1876, but to Weaver, who expected twice as many votes as he received, it was a disappointment.{{sfn|Lause|2001|pp=206<U+2013>208}}

